\begin_layout Standard
Such a framework helps us answer if the consumers in one economy may engage
 in status consumption more than they do in another.
 To compare status consumption in two different economies, we first consider
 differences in the items accessible to the consumers (i.e.
 the consumer basket) and the relative income structure (the two are referred
 to as the supply issues in the model we describe).
 Then we stardise the supply issues - availability, prices differences and
 clustering - so that the demand for status consumption can be conditioned
 on a certain level of supply.
 The fundamental issues with such a standardisation of supply are resolved
 with a notion of standard needs and the quantification of the effect of
 wealth or severe income differences on the consumer choice.
 The measure of quality (inclusive of any status consumption) in this manner
 - which is as accurate as the measurement of the cost of needs - would
